{"title_page": "Schoology", "text_new": "{{short description|Learning management system}}\n{{update|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n\n| company_logo     = [[File:Schoology Logo.svg |frameless]]\n| company_type     = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre            =\n| foundation       = [[New York, New York]] ({{Start date|2009}}) \n| founder          = {{Unbulleted list| Jeremy Friedman | Ryan Hwang | Tim Trinidad }}\n| dissolved        =\n| location         = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n| locations        =\n| incorporated     =\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Jeremy Friedman <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>\n| industry         = Education\n| products         =\n| services         =\n| revenue          =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income       =\n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = 124\n\n| parent           =\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.schoology.com}}\n| alexa            = {{Increase}} 1,330 (October 2019)\n| website_type     = Educational Social networking service / Learning Management System\n| advertising      =\n| registration     = Required\n| num_users        = \n| language         = \n| launch_date      = \n| current_status   =\n| screenshot       =\n| caption          =\n|name=Schoology}}\n\n'''Schoology''' is a very annoying website.<ref name=\"Facebook\">{{Cite web |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Conte, Henry S.| url=http://www.fbfanpost.com/2011/05/02/facebook-like-website-helps-students-and-teachers-communicate/ |title=Facebook-like Web Site Helps Students and Teachers Communicate |work=Facebook Fanpost |date=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe service includes attendance records, online gradebook, tests and quizzes, and homework dropboxes. The social media features facilitate collaboration among a class, a group, or a school.<ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Moran, Gwen |url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/217320 |title=The Rise of the Virtual Classroom |work=Entrepreneur Magazine |date=October 2010 |location=Irvine, California}}</ref>  The system can be integrated with existing school reporting and information systems<ref name=\"program\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |url=http://www.districtadministration.com/custompublishing/default.aspx?publisher=damicroportal&articleid=2517 |title=New Program Merges Learning Management and Social Media Platforms |work=District Administration |location=Norwalk, Connecticut |date=August 2010}}</ref> and also provides the  security, filters and support that school districts require.<ref name=program />\n\nThe basic product is offered to individuals, schools and districts free of charge. Revenue comes from premium add-ons such as customized branding, support packages, increased storage, single sign on, and data integration with existing [[student information system]]s (SIS).<ref name=\"raises\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Wauters, Robin |url=http://techcrunch.com/2010/06/07/schoology-raises-1-25-million-for-learning-management-software/ |title=Schoology Raises $1.25 Million for Learning Management Software |work=TechCrunch |date=June 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSchoology has partnered with other learning services such as [[McGraw-Hill Education]] and [[National Geographic Society]] [[Cengage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoology.com/partners/certified|title=Certified Partners {{!}} Schoology|website=www.schoology.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Schoology platform was designed by Jeremy Friedman, Ryan Hwang and Tim Trinidad while still undergraduates at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University in St. Louis, MO]]. Originally designed for sharing notes, Schoology was released commercially in August 2009. <ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\" />\n\nSchoology secured its first institutional round of venture capital funding of $1.25M from Meakem Becker Venture Capital in June, 2010, following an angel investment in 2009 from an unnamed investor.<ref name=program /> As of October 2010 the service had more than 2,400 schools nationwide in its system and had plans to build out interactive content that teachers can use to support course materials and provide more access to parents.<ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\" /> Enhancements have included text message notifications, mobile apps for iOS and Android, integration with Google Drive and other services, a shared resources library, and a question importer for tests and quizzes. As of October 2019 it was reported that the service is used in over 60,000 schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/schoology_partners_with_capti_to_improve_accessibility_literacy_for_struggling_readers/prweb16599294.htm|title=Schoology Partners with Capti to Improve Accessibility & Literacy for Struggling Readers|website=PRWeb|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.schoology.com Official website]\n* [http://www.appvita.com/2010/12/07/schoology-scholastic-social-networking/ Schoology \u2013 Scholastic Social Network]\n\n{{Classroom management software}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese social networking websites]]\n[[Category:Free learning management systems]]\n[[Category:Free educational software]]\n[[Category:Classroom management software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Learning management system}}\n{{update|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n\n| company_logo     = [[File:Schoology Logo.svg |frameless]]\n| company_type     = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre            =\n| foundation       = [[New York, New York]] ({{Start date|2009}}) \n| founder          = {{Unbulleted list| Jeremy Friedman | Ryan Hwang | Tim Trinidad }}\n| dissolved        =\n| location         = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n| locations        =\n| incorporated     =\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Jeremy Friedman <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>\n| industry         = Education\n| products         =\n| services         =\n| revenue          =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income       =\n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = 124\n\n| parent           =\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.schoology.com}}\n| alexa            = {{Increase}} 1,330 (October 2019)\n| website_type     = Educational Social networking service / Learning Management System\n| advertising      =\n| registration     = Required\n| num_users        = \n| language         = \n| launch_date      = \n| current_status   =\n| screenshot       =\n| caption          =\n|name=Schoology}}\n\n'''Schoology''' is a [[social networking service]] and [[virtual learning environment]] for K-12 school and higher education institutions that allows users to create, manage, and share academic content. Also known as a [[learning management system]] (LMS) or [[course management system]] (CMS), the cloud-based platform provides tools needed to manage an online classroom. Schoology can help teachers contact students with homework and more. They can post daily reminders or updates. They can message students, manage the assignment calendar and put new assignments.<ref name=\"Facebook\">{{Cite web |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Conte, Henry S.| url=http://www.fbfanpost.com/2011/05/02/facebook-like-website-helps-students-and-teachers-communicate/ |title=Facebook-like Web Site Helps Students and Teachers Communicate |work=Facebook Fanpost |date=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe service includes attendance records, online gradebook, tests and quizzes, and homework dropboxes. The social media features facilitate collaboration among a class, a group, or a school.<ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Moran, Gwen |url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/217320 |title=The Rise of the Virtual Classroom |work=Entrepreneur Magazine |date=October 2010 |location=Irvine, California}}</ref>  The system can be integrated with existing school reporting and information systems<ref name=\"program\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |url=http://www.districtadministration.com/custompublishing/default.aspx?publisher=damicroportal&articleid=2517 |title=New Program Merges Learning Management and Social Media Platforms |work=District Administration |location=Norwalk, Connecticut |date=August 2010}}</ref> and also provides the  security, filters and support that school districts require.<ref name=program />\n\nThe basic product is offered to individuals, schools and districts free of charge. Revenue comes from premium add-ons such as customized branding, support packages, increased storage, single sign on, and data integration with existing [[student information system]]s (SIS).<ref name=\"raises\">{{Cite news |accessdate =July 15, 2011 |author=Wauters, Robin |url=http://techcrunch.com/2010/06/07/schoology-raises-1-25-million-for-learning-management-software/ |title=Schoology Raises $1.25 Million for Learning Management Software |work=TechCrunch |date=June 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSchoology has partnered with other learning services such as [[McGraw-Hill Education]] and [[National Geographic Society]] [[Cengage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoology.com/partners/certified|title=Certified Partners {{!}} Schoology|website=www.schoology.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Schoology platform was designed by Jeremy Friedman, Ryan Hwang and Tim Trinidad while still undergraduates at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University in St. Louis, MO]]. Originally designed for sharing notes, Schoology was released commercially in August 2009. <ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\" />\n\nSchoology secured its first institutional round of venture capital funding of $1.25M from Meakem Becker Venture Capital in June, 2010, following an angel investment in 2009 from an unnamed investor.<ref name=program /> As of October 2010 the service had more than 2,400 schools nationwide in its system and had plans to build out interactive content that teachers can use to support course materials and provide more access to parents.<ref name=\"Virtual Classroom\" /> Enhancements have included text message notifications, mobile apps for iOS and Android, integration with Google Drive and other services, a shared resources library, and a question importer for tests and quizzes. As of October 2019 it was reported that the service is used in over 60,000 schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/schoology_partners_with_capti_to_improve_accessibility_literacy_for_struggling_readers/prweb16599294.htm|title=Schoology Partners with Capti to Improve Accessibility & Literacy for Struggling Readers|website=PRWeb|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.schoology.com Official website]\n* [http://www.appvita.com/2010/12/07/schoology-scholastic-social-networking/ Schoology \u2013 Scholastic Social Network]\n\n{{Classroom management software}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese social networking websites]]\n[[Category:Free learning management systems]]\n[[Category:Free educational software]]\n[[Category:Classroom management software]]\n", "name_user": "Jesus loves pizzza", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schoology"}
